 <i>-s</i>. The Middle English plural form was probably often in variation with the singular form. The surname is uncommon in southwestern England but may derive there from Zeals (Wiltshire), and also from the plural form of Old English <i>sealh</i> ‘willow’; see   Seal  .","Catalan, Spanish, and French (Occitan): habitational name from any of the places called Sales, like Sales de Llierca (Catalonia), from the plural of   Sala   1. Compare   De Sales  ."]},{"name":"Seales","meanings":["English: variant of   Seals  ."]}]},{"name":"Landry","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Lucien, Pierre, Emile, Andre, Fernand, Marcel, Antoine, Benoit, Camille, Raoul.","French and English (of Norman origin): from the Old French personal name <i>Landri</i>, from the ancient Germanic <i>Landric(us)</i>, a compound of <i>land</i> ‘land’ + <i>rīk</i> ‘powerful, ruler’.","English: from Middle English <i>lavendrie</i> ‘wash-house’ (Old French <i>lavanderie</i>), either a metonymic occupational name for a worker in a wash-house or a name denoting a dweller at a wash-house."],"variants":[{"name":"Lundry","meanings":["Found as a male name. Perhaps so called from being born on a Monday"]},{"name":"Londeree","meanings":["Americanized form of French (or French Canadian)   Landry  ."]},{"name":"Landrey","meanings":["French: variant of   Landry   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this. The surname <i>Landrey</i> is very rare in France."]},{"name":"Lantry","meanings":["English: variant of   Landry  ."]},{"name":"Laundry","meanings":["English (Cornwall): variant of   Landry  .","Americanized form of French (or French Canadian)   Landry  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Landry de Senlis was born about 0995, in Senlis, Oise, Picardie, France as the son of Foulques de Senlis and Mrs. Foulquer De Senlis. He had at least 1 son with Ermengarde. He died about 1080, in Chantilly, Oise